gates how international tourism development, state policies of ethnic management, and the active responses of local ethnic groups intersect to reshape ethnic identities and ethnic relations in Asian and Pacific societies. It analyzes the ways in which the very meaning of ethnicity and culture are being contested and reworked in the wake of tourism&#x0092;s impact. Following an introduction that explores the close but often ambivalent relationship between tourism promotion and state ethnic policies, individual contributors examine tourism&#x0092;s varied effects in China, Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, Indonesia, and the island Pacific in rich ethnographic detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aTourismzAsia. 0aTourismzPacific Area. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Joel S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeong, Laurence Wai-Teng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinnekin, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichaud, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOakes, Timothy S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, Michel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWood, Robert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWood, Robert E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-